<CppDocsLayout title="Input and Output" description="Read values from the terminal and display formatted output using the C++ standard streams." current="input-output" {headings} previous={{ title:'Installing C++', href:'/programming-languages/cpp/installation/' }}>
  <section id="iostream"><h2>The iostream header</h2><p>The <code>&lt;iostream&gt;</code> header provides the standard stream objects used for terminal input and output:</p><ul><li><code>std::cout</code> writes normal output.</li><li><code>std::cin</code> reads input.</li><li><code>std::cerr</code> writes error messages.</li></ul><pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;</code></pre></section>
  <section id="output"><h2>Output with cout</h2><p>Use the insertion operator <code>&lt;&lt;</code> to send values to <code>std::cout</code>. Multiple values can be chained in one statement.</p><pre><code>std::cout &lt;&lt; "Score: " &lt;&lt; 95 &lt;&lt; '\n';</code></pre><p>Prefer <code>'\n'</code> for a normal line break. <code>std::endl</code> also flushes the output buffer and is usually unnecessary.</p></section>
  <section id="input"><h2>Input with cin</h2><p>Use the extraction operator <code>&gt;&gt;</code> to read a formatted value into a variable. The input must be compatible with the variable's type.</p><pre><code>int age&#123;&#125;;

std::cout &lt;&lt; "Enter your age: ";
std::cin &gt;&gt; age;
std::cout &lt;&lt; "You are " &lt;&lt; age &lt;&lt; " years old.\n";</code></pre></section>
  <section id="multiple-values"><h2>Reading multiple values</h2><p>Extraction operations can be chained. Whitespace separates the values typed by the user.</p><pre><code>int width&#123;&#125;;
int height&#123;&#125;;

std::cout &lt;&lt; "Enter width and height: ";
std::cin &gt;&gt; width &gt;&gt; height;

std::cout &lt;&lt; "Area: " &lt;&lt; width * height &lt;&lt; '\n';</code></pre></section>
  <section id="full-lines"><h2>Reading full lines</h2><p><code>std::cin &gt;&gt;</code> stops at whitespace. Use <code>std::getline</code> when the input may contain spaces.</p><pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;

std::string name;
std::cout &lt;&lt; "Enter your full name: ";
std::getline(std::cin, name);
std::cout &lt;&lt; "Hello, " &lt;&lt; name &lt;&lt; "!\n";</code></pre><div class="callout"><p>After using <code>std::cin &gt;&gt;</code>, consume the remaining newline with <code>std::getline(std::cin &gt;&gt; std::ws, value)</code> before reading a complete line.</p></div></section>
  <section id="formatting"><h2>Formatting output</h2><p>The <code>&lt;iomanip&gt;</code> header provides tools for controlling numeric output.</p><pre><code>#include &lt;iomanip&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;

double price&#123;19.5&#125;;
std::cout &lt;&lt; std::fixed &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(2)
          &lt;&lt; "$" &lt;&lt; price &lt;&lt; '\n';

// Output: $19.50</code></pre></section>
  <section id="complete-example"><h2>Complete example</h2><p>This program reads a product name, price, and quantity, then prints a formatted total.</p><pre><code>#include &lt;iomanip&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;

int main() &#123;
    std::string product;
    double price&#123;&#125;;
    int quantity&#123;&#125;;

    std::cout &lt;&lt; "Product: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, product);

    std::cout &lt;&lt; "Price and quantity: ";
    std::cin &gt;&gt; price &gt;&gt; quantity;

    const double total&#123;price * quantity&#125;;
    std::cout &lt;&lt; std::fixed &lt;&lt; std::setprecision(2)
              &lt;&lt; product &lt;&lt; " total: $" &lt;&lt; total &lt;&lt; '\n';

    return 0;
&#125;</code></pre></section>
</CppDocsLayout>
